03812nmm a2200529Ia 9781438482422DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20212021nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814384824227 a10.1515/97814384824222doi  a(DE-B1597)682545  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aBL1138.26b.M36 2021eb 7aLIT0080202bisacsh04a294.5/923223  aEU 2010qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/161155:00aMany Mahābhāratas /ced. by Sohini Sarah Pillai, Nell Shapiro Hawley. 1aAlbany : bSUNY Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (462 p.) :bTotal Illustrations: 7  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSUNY series in Hindu Studies0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMany Mahābhāratas is an introduction to the spectacular and long-lived diversity of Mahābhārata literature in South Asia. This diversity begins with the Sanskrit Mahābhārata, an early epic poem that narrates the events of a catastrophic fratricidal war. Along the way, it draws in nearly everything else in Hindu mythology, philosophy, and story literature. The magnitude of its scope and the relentless complexity of its worldview primed the Mahābhārata for uncountable tellings in South Asia and beyond. For two thousand years, the instinctive approach to the Mahābhārata has been not to consume it but to create it anew.The many Mahābhāratas of this book come from the first century to the twenty-first. They are composed in nine different languages—Apabhramsha, Bengali, English, Hindi, Kannada, Malayalam, Sanskrit, Tamil, and Telugu. Early chapters illuminate themes of retelling within the Sanskrit Mahābhārata itself, demonstrating that the story's propensity for regeneration emerges from within. The majority of the book, however, reaches far beyond the Sanskrit epic. Readers dive into classical dramas, premodern vernacular poems, regional performance traditions, commentaries, graphic novels, political essays, novels, and contemporary theater productions—all of them Mahābhāratas.Because of its historical and linguistic breadth, its commitment to primary sources, and its exploration of multiplicity and diversity as essential features of the Mahābhārata's long life in South Asia, Many Mahābhāratas constitutes a major contribution to the study of South Asian literature and offers a landmark view of the field of Mahābhārata studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 4aAsian Studies : Asian Literature. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Religion and Philosophy. 4aAsian Studies : India and South Asian Studies. 4aLiterature : Comparative Literature. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Hindu Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Asian / Indic.2bisacsh1 aHawley, Nell Shapiro, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPillai, Sohini Sarah, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143848242240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438482422423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438482422/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles